  "text": "Not only do some kinds of social behavior create opiatemediated stress behaviors, but lack of social behavior also does. Isolation of rat pups induced ultrasonic vocalizations that were attenuated by morphine, [D-Ala2,N-MePhe4,Gly~ol]enkephalin (DAMGO), or [D-Pen2'5]enkephalin (DPDPE), but did not induce analgesia [CITATION_1] . Hypertension that occurred in rat pups subjected to isolation was probably mediated by the endogenous opiate system, because chronic treatment with morphine inhibited it, and withdrawal of the morphine resulted in a return to high arterial pressure [CITATION_2] . Even undisturbed in the home cage in the presence of their littermates, a situation that rarely produces ultrasonic vocalizations, injection of U50,488 [(+_)-trans-3,4-dichloro-Nmethyl-N-(2-(l-pyrrolidinyl)cyclohexyl) benzeneacetamide], a highly selective K agonist, elicited ultrasonic vocalizations and other signs of stress. Naltrexone had no effect [CITATION_3] , however, calling into question the role of the endogenous opiate system in the reaction.",
